description.narrative: 1.1 By 2021, health care policymakers and service providers are equipped with knowledge, guidance, tools and mechanisms to effectively scale up and implement the new Maternal, Neonatal, and Child Health (MNCH) normative framework, focused on the most marginalized., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Health Systems Strengthening, Immunization, Maternal And Newborn Health, Nutrition â€“ General, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Strengthened Governance for Equity and Social Inclusion Outcome Result:By 2021, children in situations of particular vulnerability enjoy equitable access to quality health, education and social protection services supported by effective governance mechanisms.

description.narrative: UNICEF work in 2021 was twofold, supporting the country response for COVID-19 and ensure continuity of maternal and child health services. School-age nutrition was the focus of multiple sectors including health, education, agriculture with important knowledge base on iodine nutrition and milestone achievement in improving the regulatory framework related to food standards in the school settings and regulation of the marketing of the unhealthy foods in education institutions. UNICEF provided technical inputs for the development of important sector documents including Health Strategy, NCD action plan, Reproductive Health plan. UNICEF supported procurement for childhood vaccines, ARVs, COVID-19 vaccine through COVAX. | Status:Met | As-of Date:24/01/2022
